Patch Set 5:

"To use a media rule other than the default "screen" rule,
specify it before calling setHtml() with setMetaInformation()
and the new info value 'CssMedia'."

This implies the media can only be pre-selected at the time of setHtml(). The most common usage of CSS media, however, is to include the "print" media. With that in mind, how would one go about getting print() to print using "print" media if such was present in the stylesheet? Shouldn't this be done implicitly by print() itself?

Patch Set 5:

> Patch Set 5:
> 
> "To use a media rule other than the default "screen" rule,
> specify it before calling setHtml() with setMetaInformation()
> and the new info value 'CssMedia'."
> 
> This implies the media can only be pre-selected at the time of setHtml(). The most common usage of CSS media, however, is to include the "print" media. With that in mind, how would one go about getting print() to print using "print" media if such was present in the stylesheet? Shouldn't this be done implicitly by print() itself?

You know about Qt's architectural limitation though right?  We only have code to parse CSS and HTML simultaneously: we save what we save, in memory (QTextBlock and related classes), and then the rest of the information from those is lost.  QTextDocument is almost a DOM, but not quite.  So we don't have code to parse html first and then CSS later on, because not quite enough info from the HTML is retained to be able to do that.  (IMO that needs fixing eventually, but it might be a big change.)

Not sure whether we should only set it for -optimize-size though.

Patch Set 2:

> Not sure whether we should only set it for -optimize-size though.

In my opinion, it's safe to enable /Gw unconditionally for release builds. If I understand the documentation correctly, the principle of why this parameter can make the generated binary file smaller is something like dead code elimination, it's not like the /O1 parameter, which is to turn off some optimization to reduce the file size, which obviously might have a compact for the performance. Microsoft Docs don't mention anything about whether /Gw will affect the performance or not, and from its principle, I can't find anything that might influence the performance either. If enabling /Gw really has some significant side-effects, I think the official documentation would say something about them.

For the parameters that should be in the -optimize-size scope, I think they should be the ones that might influence the performance, because some users may can't accept performance lose.

The other way. Current we only use OpenGL. But the idea is to use ANGLE internally in qtwebengine, and then have ANGLE export D3D textures. There is this https://github.com/google/angle/blob/master/extensions/EGL_ANGLE_surface_d3d_texture_2d_share_handle.txt but it requires making an EGL(angle) surface and then get a D3D handle from that.
